#: src/porting-applications.md:76
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:78
msgid "This section contain quick important information for porting."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:80
msgid ""
"Most or all build instructions were made for native compilation and not "
"cross-compilation, with some poor documentation exceptions"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:81
msgid ""
"If the application or library build tests in compilation you need to disable "
"them for cross-compilation"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:82
msgid ""
"If you are using dynamic linking and the `custom` recipe template, the "
"`DYNAMIC_INIT` command need to be added in the first line of the `script` "
"data type"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:83
msgid ""
"We recommend to use the FreeBSD dependencies of the application if available "
"because Linux dependencies tend to contain Linux-specific kernel features "
"not available on Redox (unfortunately the FreeBSD package naming policy "
"don't separate library objects/interpreters from build tools in all cases, "
"thus you need to know or search each item to know if it's a library, "
"interpreter or build tool)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:84
msgid ""
"Debian packages are the most easy way to find dependencies because they are "
"the most used by software developers to describe \"Build Instructions\" "
"dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:85
msgid ""
"Don't use the `.deb` packages to create recipes, they are adapted for the "
"Debian environment."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:86
msgid ""
"The Debian naming policy use dashes as separators in packages with optional "
"features: `application-name` (default application variant with compiled "
"executables) and `application-name-dev` (application variant with objects "
"for linking), also check the source package to be sure"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:87
msgid ""
"The recipe `PATH` environment variable only read build tool recipes declared "
"in the `build.dev-dependencies` data type or the host system's `/usr/bin` "
"directory, it can't read the `/usr/lib` and `/include` folders because the "
"Linux library objects don't work on Redox."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:88
msgid ""
"The recipe support recursive dependencies, thus you don't need to specify a "
"dependency two times if some dependency already provide it"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:89
msgid ""
"Don't add build tools in the `build.dependencies` data type, check the "
"[Debian](https://packages.debian.org/stable/build-essential) and [Arch Linux]"
"(https://archlinux.org/packages/core/any/base-devel/) meta-packages for a "
"common reference of build tools."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:90
msgid ""
"The compiler can build recipe dependency libraries as `.so` files (objects "
"for dynamic linking) or `.a` files (objects for static linking): The `.so` "
"files will be installed out of the binary (stored on the `/lib` directory of "
"the system) while the `.a` files will be mixed in the final binary."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:91
msgid ""
"Linux distributions add a number after the `.so` files to avoid conflicts on "
"the `/usr/lib` folder when applications use different API versions of the "
"same library, for example: `library-name.so.6`"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:93
msgid ""
"You need to know the above information because each software is different, "
"the major reason is the \"Build Instructions\" organization and context of "
"each application or library."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:95
msgid "Recipe"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:97
msgid ""
"A recipe is how we call a software port on Redox, this section explain the "
"recipe configuration and details to consider."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:99
msgid ""
"Create a folder at `recipes/application-category` with a file named as "
"`recipe.toml` inside, we will modify this file to fit the application needs."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:101
msgid "Recipe creation from terminal with GNU Nano:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:115
msgid "Recipe Configuration Example"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:117
msgid ""
"The recipe configuration (`recipe.toml`) example below contain all supported "
"recipe options. Adapt for your script, application, library or data files."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:119
msgid ""
"TOML sections and data types can also be mentioned using the `section-name."
"data-type-name` format for easier explanation and better explanation writing."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:121
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[source]\n"
"git = \"repository-link\" # source.git data type\n"
"upstream = \"repository-link\" # source.upstream data type\n"
"branch = \"branch-name\" # source.branch data type\n"
"rev = \"version-tag\" # source.rev data type\n"
"shallow_clone = true # source.shallow_clone data type\n"
"tar = \"tarball-link.tar.gz\" # source.tar data type\n"
"blake3 = \"source-hash\" # source.blake3 data type\n"
"patches = [ # source.patches data type\n"
"    \"patch1.patch\",\n"
"    \"patch2.patch\",\n"
"]\n"
"same_as = \"../application-name\" # source.same_as data type\n"
"script = \"\"\" # source.script data type\n"
"insert your script here\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"[build]\n"
"template = \"build-system\" # build.template data type\n"
"cargopath = \"package-directory\" # build.cargopath\n"
"cargopackages = [ # build.cargopackages\n"
"    \"package1\",\n"
"    \"package2\",\n"
"]\n"
"cargoexamples = [ # build.cargoexamples\n"
"    \"example1\",\n"
"    \"example2\",\n"
"]\n"
"cargoflags = [\"--option-name\"] # build.cargoflags data type\n"
"configureflags = [ # build.configureflags data type\n"
"    \"OPTION1=value\",\n"
"    \"OPTION2=value\",\n"
"]\n"
"cmakeflags = [ # build.cmakeflags data type\n"
"    \"-DOPTION1=value\",\n"
"    \"-DOPTION2=value\",\n"
"]\n"
"mesonflags = [ # build.mesonflags data type\n"
"    \"-Doption1=value\",\n"
"    \"-Doption2=value\",\n"
"]\n"
"dev-dependencies = [ # build.dev-dependencies data type\n"
"    \"host:tool1\",\n"
"    \"host:tool2\",\n"
"]\n"
"dependencies = [ # build.dependencies data type\n"
"    \"library1\",\n"
"    \"library2\",\n"
"]\n"
"script = \"\"\" # build.script data type\n"
"# Uncomment the following if the package can be dynamically linked\n"
"#DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"insert your script here\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"[package]\n"
"dependencies = [ # package.dependencies data type\n"
"    \"runtime-dependency1\",\n"
"    \"runtime-dependency2\",\n"
"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:182
msgid ""
"`[source]` : Section for data types that manage the application source (only "
"remove it if you have a `source` folder)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:183
msgid ""
"`source.git` : Git repository of the application (can be removed if a Git "
"repository is not used), you can comment out it to not allow Cookbook to "
"force a `git pull` or change the active branch to `master` or `main`. Read "
"the [Git Repositories](#git-repositories) section for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:184
msgid ""
"`source.upstream` : If you are using a fork of the application source with "
"patches add the application upstream source here (can be removed if the "
"upstream source is being used on the `git` data type)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:185
msgid ""
"`source.branch` : application version Git branch or patched Git branch (can "
"be removed if using a tarball or the `master` or `main` Git branches are "
"being used)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:186
msgid ""
"`source.rev` : Git tag or commit hash of the latest stable version or last "
"working commit of the application (can be removed if you are using a tarball "
"or waiting Rust library version updates)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:187
msgid ""
"`source.shallow_clone` : Boolean data type to only download the current "
"commit of source files (Git [shallow clone](https://github.blog/open-source/"
"git/get-up-to-speed-with-partial-clone-and-shallow-clone/)), which can "
"reduce the download/delta processing time a lot and save many storage space "
"(insert `shallow_clone = true`). Read the note in the [Git Repositories]"
"(#git-repositories) section if you are doing heavy development in a fork"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:188
msgid ""
"`source.tar` : application source tarball (can be removed if a tarball is "
"not used), read the [Tarballs](#tarballs) section for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:189
msgid ""
"`source.blake3` : application source tarball BLAKE3 hash, can be generated "
"using the `b3sum` tool, install with the `cargo install b3sum` command (can "
"be removed if using a Git repository or under porting)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:190
msgid ""
"`source.patches` : Data type to load `.patch` files (can be removed if patch "
"files aren't used)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:191
msgid ""
"`\"patch1.patch\",` : The patch file name (can be removed if the `patches` "
"data type above is not present)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:192
msgid ""
"`source.same_as` : Insert the folder of other recipe to make a symbolic link "
"to the `source` folder of other recipe, useful if you want modularity with "
"synchronization"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:193
msgid ""
"`source.script` : Data type used when you need to change the build system "
"configuration (to regenerate the GNU Autotools configuration, for example)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:194
msgid ""
"`[build]` : Section for data types that manage the application compilation "
"and packaging"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:195
msgid ""
"`build.template` : Insert the application build system, read the [Templates]"
"(#templates) section for more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:196
msgid ""
"`build.cargopath` : Data type for Cargo package directory path (when `Cargo."
"toml` is missing in repository/tarball root directory or when package is not "
"declared in the root directory workspace)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:197
msgid "`build.cargopackages` : Data type for Cargo packages"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:198
msgid "`build.cargoexamples` : Data type for Cargo examples"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:199
msgid "`build.cargoflags` : Data type for Cargo flags (array)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:200
msgid "`build.configureflags` : Data type for GNU Autotools flags (array)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:201
msgid "`build.cmakeflags` : Data type for CMake flags (array)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:202
msgid "`build.mesonflags` : Data type for Meson flags (array)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:203
msgid ""
"`build.dev-dependencies` : Data type to add the build tools needed by the "
"application or library"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:204
msgid ""
"`build.dev-dependencies = [\"host:tool1\",]` : Build tool recipe name (can "
"be removed if the `build.dev-dependencies` data type is not present)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:205
msgid ""
"`build.dependencies` : Data type to add dynamically or statically linked "
"library dependencies, read the [Dependencies](#dependencies) section for "
"more details."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:206
msgid ""
"`build.dependencies = [\"library1\",]` : Library recipe name (can be removed "
"if the `build.dependencies` data type is not present)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:207
msgid ""
"`build.script` : Data type to load the custom commands for compilation and "
"packaging"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:208
msgid ""
"`[package]` : Section for data types that manage the application package"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:209
msgid ""
"`package.dependencies` : Data type to add tools, interpreters or \"data "
"files\" recipes to be installed by the package manager or build system "
"installer"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:210
msgid ""
"`package.dependencies = [\"runtime-dependency1\",]` : Tool, interpreter or "
"data recipe names (can be removed if the `package.dependencies` data type "
"above is not present)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:212
msgid "Quick Recipe Template"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:214
msgid "This is a recipe template for a quick porting workflow."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:216
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"#TODO not compiled or tested\n"
"[source]\n"
"git = \"repository-link\"\n"
"rev = \"version-tag\"\n"
"branch = \"version-branch\"\n"
"tar = \"tarball-link\"\n"
"shallow_clone = true\n"
"[build]\n"
"template = \"build-system\"\n"
"dependencies = [\n"
"    \"library1\",\n"
"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:231
msgid ""
"You can quickly copy and paste this template on each `recipe.toml`, that way "
"you spent less time writting and has less chances for typos."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:233
msgid ""
"If your application use a tarball, you can quickly remove the `git` and "
"`rev` data types."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:234
msgid ""
"If your application use a Git repository, you can quickly remove the `tar` "
"data type."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:235
msgid ""
"If you don't need to pin a Git tag or commit hash for the latest stable "
"release or last working commit, you can quickly remove the `rev` data type."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:236
msgid ""
"If the application don't need C, C++ or patched Rust dependencies, you can "
"quickly remove the `dependencies = []` section."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:238
msgid "After the `#TODO` comment you will write your current porting status."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:240
msgid "Cookbook"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:242
msgid ""
"The GCC and LLVM compiler frontends on Linux use the Linux target triplet by "
"default, it will create Linux ELF binaries that don't work on Redox because "
"it can't undertstand them."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:244
msgid ""
"Part of this process is to use `glibc` (GNU C Standard Library) which don't "
"support Redox system calls, to make the compiler use `relibc` (Redox C "
"Standard Library) Cookbook need to tell the build system of the application "
"or library to use it, it's done with environment variables and target/"
"platform flags for the Redox target."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:246
msgid ""
"Cookbook have build system templates to avoid custom commands for cross-"
"compilation, but it's not always possible because some build systems or "
"applications aren't standardized or adapted for cross-compilation."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:248
msgid ""
"(Build systems have different methods to enable cross-compilation and pass a "
"different C standard library to the compiler, you will need to read their "
"documentation, application/library specific configuration or hack them)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:250
msgid "Cross Compiler"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:252
msgid ""
"Cookbook use Rust/GCC forks to do cross-compilation of recipes "
"(applications) with `relibc` to any supported CPU architecture, you can "
"check our cross-compilers on GitLab ([GCC](https://gitlab.redox-os.org/redox-"
"os/gcc), [LLVM](https://gitlab.redox-os.org/redox-os/llvm-project), [Rust]"
"(https://gitlab.redox-os.org/redox-os/rust) and their [pre-compiled binaries]"
"(https://static.redox-os.org/toolchain/))."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:254
msgid "Cross Compilation"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:256
msgid ""
"The Cookbook default compilation type is cross-compilation because it "
"reduces the requirements to run applications on Redox and allow us to do "
"Redox development from Linux and other Unix-like systems."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:258
msgid ""
"By default Cookbook use the CPU architecture of your host system but you can "
"change it easily on your `.config` file (`ARCH?` environment variable)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:260
msgid ""
"Don't use a hardcoded CPU architecture in the `script` data types of your "
"`recipe.toml`, it breaks cross-compilation with a different CPU architecture "
"is used by the build system."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:261
msgid ""
"All recipes must use our cross-compilers, a Cookbook template does this "
"automatically but it's not always possible, read the build system "
"configuration of your application/library to find these options or patch the "
"configuration files."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:263
msgid "Templates"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:265
msgid ""
"A recipe template is the build system of the application or library "
"supported by Cookbook."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:267
msgid ""
"`template = \"cargo\"` - Build with Cargo using cross-compilation and static "
"linking (Rust applications with one package in the Cargo workspace)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:268
msgid ""
"`template = \"configure\"` - Build with GNU Autotools/GNU Make using cross-"
"compilation and dynamic linking."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:269
msgid ""
"`template = \"cmake\"` - Build with CMake using cross-compilation and "
"dynamic linking."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:270
msgid ""
"`template = \"meson\"` - Build with Meson using cross-compilation and "
"dynamic linking."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:271
msgid ""
"`template = \"remote\"` - Download the remote Redox package of the recipe if "
"available in the [package server](https://static.redox-os.org/pkg/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:272
msgid ""
"`template = \"custom\"` - Run your commands on the `script =` field and "
"build (Any build system or installation process)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:274
msgid ""
"Keep in mind that some recipes may need build tools that aren't provided by "
"the build system templates or not installed in the Podman container or your "
"system and will need to be added in the `dev.dependencies` data type of the "
"recipe, don't add build tools or compilers already provided by the templates."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:276
msgid ""
"The `script =` field runs any terminal command supported by GNU Bash, it's "
"important if the build system of the application don't support cross-"
"compilation or need custom options to work on Redox (you can't use the "
"`build.script` data type if the `custom` template is not used)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:278
msgid ""
"Each template (except `custom`) script supports build flags, you can add "
"flags as an array of strings:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:280
msgid "`cargoflags = \"foo\"`"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:281
msgid "`configureflags = [ \"foo\" ]`"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:282
msgid "`cmakeflags = [ \"foo\" ]`"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:283
msgid "`mesonflags = [ \"foo\" ]`"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:285
msgid ""
"To find the supported Cookbook Bash functions, look the recipes using a "
"`script =` field on their `recipe.toml` or read the [source code](https://"
"gitlab.redox-os.org/redox-os/redox/-/tree/master/src)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:287
msgid ""
"[Recipes](https://gitlab.redox-os.org/redox-os/redox/-/tree/master/recipes)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:289
msgid "Cases"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:291
msgid "applications using the Cargo build system have a `Cargo.toml` file"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:292
msgid ""
"applications using the GNU Autotools build system have a `configure` or "
"`autogen.sh` file in the source tarball"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:293
msgid "applications using the CMake build system have a `CMakeLists.txt` file"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:294
msgid "applications using the Meson build system have a `meson.build` file"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:296
msgid "Metapackages"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:298
msgid ""
"Metapackages are packages without any files, just dependencies. Use the "
"following recipe example to create a metapackage:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:300
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[package]\n"
"dependencies = [\n"
"    \"package1\",\n"
"    \"package2\",\n"
"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:308
msgid "Cookbook - Custom Template"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:310
msgid ""
"The `custom` template enable the `build.script =` data type to be used, this "
"data type will run any command supported by the [GNU Bash](https://www.gnu."
"org/software/bash/) shell. The shell script will be wrapped with Bash "
"functions and variables to aid the build script. The wrapper can be found in "
"[this Cookbook source file](https://gitlab.redox-os.org/redox-os/-/blob/"
"master/src/bin/cook.rs)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:313
msgid "Script example"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:315
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[build]\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"first-command\n"
"second-command\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:323
msgid ""
"The script section starts at the location of the `${COOKBOOK_BUILD}` "
"environment variable (`recipe-name/target/$TARGET/build`). This "
"`${COOKBOOK_BUILD}` will be an empty folder, while recipe sources are in "
"`${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}`. It is expected that the build script will not modify "
"anything in `${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}`, otherwise, please use the `source.script = "
"` data type."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:325
msgid "Functions"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:327
msgid ""
"Each template has a Bash function to be used in the `script` data type when "
"you need to customize the template configuration to fix the application "
"compilation or enable/disable features."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:329
msgid "`cookbook_cargo` - Bash function of the `cargo` template"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:330
msgid "`cookbook_configure` - Bash function of the `configure` template"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:331
msgid "`cookbook_cmake` - Bash function of the `cmake` template"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:332
msgid "`cookbook_meson` - Bash function of the `meson` template"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:333
msgid ""
"`DYNAMIC_INIT` - Bash function to configure the recipe to be dynamically "
"linked"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:334
msgid ""
"`DYNAMIC_STATIC_INIT` - Bash function to configure the recipe to be both "
"statically and dynamically linked (library recipe only)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:336 src/porting-applications.md:1084
msgid "Environment Variables"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:338
msgid "These variables available in the script:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:340
msgid "`${TARGET}` - Redox compiler triple target (`$ARCH-unknown-redox`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:341
msgid "`${GNU_TARGET}` - Redox compiler triple target (GNU variant)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:342
msgid "`${COOKBOOK_MAKE_JOBS}` - Total CPU threads available"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:343
msgid "`${COOKBOOK_RECIPE}` - Recipe folder."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:344
msgid "`${COOKBOOK_ROOT}` - The Cookbook directory."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:345
msgid ""
"`${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}` - The `source` folder at `recipe-name/source` "
"(application source)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:346
msgid ""
"`${COOKBOOK_SYSROOT}` - The `sysroot` folder at `recipe-name/target/$TARGET/"
"sysroot` (library sources)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:347
msgid ""
"`${COOKBOOK_BUILD}` - The `build` folder at `recipe-name/target/$TARGET/"
"build` (recipe build system)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:348
msgid ""
"`${COOKBOOK_STAGE}` - The `stage` folder at `recipe-name/target/$TARGET/"
"stage` (recipe binaries)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:350
msgid ""
"For RISC-V, `${TARGET}` and `${GNU_TARGET}` is `riscv64gc-unknown-redox` and "
"`riscv64-unknown-redox`, usually you want `${TARGET}` unless the script "
"requires a GNU target triple."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:351
msgid ""
"To get `$ARCH`, you need to add `ARCH=\"${TARGET%%-*}\"` to the beginning of "
"the script."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:353
msgid ""
"There are more variables depending on the build script that you are using."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:355
msgid ""
"We recommend that you use path environment variables with the `\"` symbol to "
"clean any invalid characters (like spaces) on the path, spaces are "
"interpreted as command separators and will break the path."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:357 src/porting-applications.md:1028
#: src/porting-applications.md:1037 src/porting-applications.md:1048
#: src/porting-applications.md:1090
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:360 src/porting-applications.md:366
msgid "\"${VARIABLE_NAME}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:363
msgid "If you have a folder inside the variable folder you can call it with:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:368 src/porting-applications.md:1380
msgid "Or"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:370
msgid "\"${VARIABLE_NAME}/folder-name\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:373
msgid "Quick Template"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:375
msgid "You can quickly copy these environment variables from this section."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:378
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}/\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:382
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_BUILD}/\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:386
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_SYSROOT}/\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:390
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}/\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:393
msgid "Packaging Behavior"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:395
msgid ""
"Cookbook download the recipe sources on the `source` folder (`recipe-name/"
"source`), copy the contents of this folder to the `build` folder (`recipe-"
"name/target/$TARGET/build`), build the sources and move the binaries to the "
"`stage` folder (`recipe-name/target/$TARGET/stage`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:397
msgid ""
"If your recipe has library dependencies, it will copy the library source and "
"linker objects to the `sysroot` folder to be used by the `build` folder."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:399
msgid "Moving the application files to the Redox filesystem"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:401
msgid ""
"The `\"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/` path is used to specify where the recipe files "
"will be stored in the Redox filesystem, in most cases `/usr/bin` and `/usr/"
"lib`."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:403
msgid "You can see path examples for most customized recipes below:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:406 src/porting-applications.md:452
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:406
msgid ""
"# The root of the Redox build system\n"
"\"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:407
msgid ""
"# System-wide executables directory\n"
"\"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:408
msgid ""
"# System-wide shared and static library objects directory\n"
"\"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:409
msgid ""
"# System-wide application static data files\n"
"\"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:410
msgid "# System-wide application static configuration files\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:413
msgid "GNU Autotools script"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:415
msgid ""
"Use this script if the application or library needs to be compiled with "
"custom options"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:417
msgid "Configure with dynamic linking"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:419
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"COOKBOOK_CONFIGURE_FLAGS+=(\n"
"    --option1\n"
"    --option2\n"
")\n"
"cookbook_configure\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:430
msgid "GNU Make without Configure"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:432
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"COOKBOOK_CONFIGURE_FLAGS+=(\n"
"    --option1\n"
"    --option2\n"
")\n"
"COOKBOOK_CONFIGURE=\"true\"\n"
"\n"
"rsync -av --delete \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}/\" ./\n"
"cookbook_configure\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:446
msgid "Definition of `cookbook_configure` is roughly:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:450
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_CONFIGURE}\" \"${COOKBOOK_CONFIGURE_FLAGS[@]}\" \"$@\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:451 src/porting-applications.md:452
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_MAKE}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:451 src/porting-applications.md:506
#: src/porting-applications.md:507
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_MAKE_JOBS}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:456
msgid "GNU Autotools configuration script"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:458
msgid ""
"Sometimes the application tarball or repository is lacking the `configure` "
"script or it need to be recreated for dynamic linking, so you will need to "
"generate this script."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:460
msgid "Add the following code below the `[source]` section"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:462
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"autotools_recursive_regenerate\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:468
msgid "CMake script"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:470
msgid ""
"Use this script for applications using the CMake build system, more CMake "
"options can be added with a `-D` before them, the customization of CMake "
"compilation is very easy."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:472
msgid "CMake using dynamic linking"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:474
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"COOKBOOK_CMAKE_FLAGS+=(\n"
"    -DOPTION1=value\n"
"    -DOPTION2=value\n"
")\n"
"cookbook_cmake\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:485
msgid "CMake inside a subfolder"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:487
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"COOKBOOK_CMAKE_FLAGS+=(\n"
"    -DOPTION1=value\n"
"    -DOPTION2=value\n"
")\n"
"cookbook_cmake \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}\"/subfolder\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:498
msgid "Definition of `cookbook_cmake` is roughly:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:502
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_CMAKE}\" \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:503
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_CMAKE_FLAGS[@]}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:504
msgid "\"$@\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:506
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_NINJA}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:507
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\" \"${COOKBOOK_NINJA}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:512
msgid "Meson script"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:514
msgid ""
"Use this script for applications using the Meson build system, more Meson "
"options can be added with a `-D` before them, the customization of Meson "
"compilation is very easy."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:516
msgid ""
"Keep in mind that some applications and libraries need more configuration to "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:518
msgid "Meson using dynamic linking"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:520
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"COOKBOOK_MESON_FLAGS+=(\n"
"    -Doption1=value\n"
"    -Doption2=value\n"
")\n"
"cookbook_meson\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:531
msgid "Meson inside a subfolder"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:533
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"COOKBOOK_MESON_FLAGS+=(\n"
"    -Doption1=value\n"
"    -Doption2=value\n"
")\n"
"cookbook_meson \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}\"/subfolder\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:544
msgid "Cargo script"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:546
msgid "Use this script if you need to customize the `cookbook_cargo` function."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:548
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"COOKBOOK_CARGO_FLAGS=(\n"
"    --bin foo\n"
")\n"
"PACKAGE_PATH=\"subfolder\" cookbook_cargo \"${COOKBOOK_CARGO_FLAGS[@]}\"\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:558
msgid ""
"If the project is roughly a simple Cargo project then `cookbook_cargo` is "
"all that you need."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:560
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"cookbook_cargo\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:568
msgid "Analyze the source code of a Rust application"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:570
msgid ""
"Rust applications and libraries use the `Cargo.toml` configuration file to "
"configure the build system and source code."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:572
msgid ""
"While packaging Rust applications you need to know where the main executable "
"is located in the Cargo project, to do this you need to verify the `Cargo."
"toml` files of the project."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:574
msgid ""
"A Rust application can have one or more Cargo packages to build, read the "
"common assumptions below:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:576
msgid ""
"Most Rust applications with a `src` folder use one Cargo package, thus you "
"can use the `cargo` template."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:577
msgid ""
"Most Rust applications with multiple Cargo packages name the main package "
"with the name of the application."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:579
msgid "Beyond these common source code organization, there are special cases."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:581
msgid ""
"In some Rust applications the `Cargo.toml` file contains one of these data "
"types:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:583
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[[bin]]\n"
"name = \"executable-name\"\n"
"[[lib]]\n"
"name = \"library-object-name\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:590
msgid ""
"The `[[bin]]` is what you need, the application executable is built by this "
"Cargo package."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:592
msgid ""
"But some applications don't have the `[[bin]]` and `[[lib]]` data types, for "
"these cases you need to see the source code files, in most cases at the "
"`src` folder."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:594
msgid "The file named `main.rs` contains the application executable code."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:595
msgid "The file named `lib.rs` contains the library object code (ignore it)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:597
msgid ""
"(Some Rust applications use packages instead of example files for examples, "
"to discover that see if the \"examples\" folder has `.rs` files (examples "
"files) or folders with `Cargo.toml` files inside (packages) )"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:599
msgid "Cargo packages command example"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:601
msgid ""
"This command is used for Rust applications that use package folders inside "
"the repository for compilation, you need to use the name on the `name` field "
"below the `[package]` section of the `Cargo.toml` file inside the package "
"folder (generally using the same name of the application)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:603
msgid ""
"(This will fix the \"found virtual manifest instead of package manifest\" "
"error)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:605
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"cookbook_cargo_packages application-name\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:612
msgid ""
"(You can use `cookbook_cargo_packages application1 application2` if it's "
"more than one package)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:614
msgid "Cargo package with flags"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:616
msgid ""
"If you need a script for a package with flags (customization), you can use "
"this script:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:618
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"package=package-name\n"
"\"${COOKBOOK_CARGO}\" build \\\n"
"            --manifest-path \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}/Cargo.toml\" \\\n"
"            --package \"${package}\" \\\n"
"            --release \\\n"
"            --add-your-flag-here\n"
"        mkdir -pv \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}/usr/bin\"\n"
"        cp -v \\\n"
"            \"target/${TARGET}/release/${package}\" \\\n"
"            \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}/usr/bin/${package}\"\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:634
msgid ""
"The `package-name` after `package=` is where you will insert the Cargo "
"package name of your application."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:635
msgid "The `--add-your-flag-here` will be replaced by the application flag."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:637
msgid "Cargo bins script example"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:639
msgid ""
"Some Rust applications use bins instead of packages to build, to build them "
"you can use this script:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:641
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"binary=bin-name\n"
"\"${COOKBOOK_CARGO}\" build \\\n"
"            --manifest-path \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}/Cargo.toml\" \\\n"
"            --bin \"${binary}\" \\\n"
"            --release \\\n"
"            --add-your-flag-here\n"
"        mkdir -pv \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}/usr/bin\"\n"
"        cp -v \\\n"
"            \"target/${TARGET}/release/${binary}\" \\\n"
"            \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}/usr/bin/${binary}\"\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:657
msgid ""
"The `bin-name` after `binary=` is where you will insert the Cargo package "
"name of your application."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:658
msgid "The `--add-your-flag-here` will be replaced by the application flags."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:660
msgid "Cargo flags command example"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:662
msgid ""
"Some Rust applications have flags for customization, you can find them below "
"the `[features]` section in the `Cargo.toml` file."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:664
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"cookbook_cargo --features flag-name\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:671
msgid "Disable the default Cargo flags"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:673
msgid ""
"It's common that some flag of the application doesn't work on Redox, if you "
"don't want to spend much time testing flags that work and don't work, you "
"can disable all of them to see if the most basic featureset of the "
"application works with this script:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:675
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"cookbook_cargo --no-default-features\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:682
msgid "Enable all Cargo flags"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:684
msgid "If you want to enable all flags of the application, use:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:686
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"cookbook_cargo --all-features\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:693
msgid "Cargo profiles command example"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:695
msgid "This script is used for Rust applications using Cargo profiles."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:697
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"cookbook_cargo --profile profile-name\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:704
msgid "Cargo examples command example"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:706
msgid "This script is used for examples on Rust applications."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:708
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"cookbook_cargo_examples example-name\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:715
msgid ""
"(You can use `cookbook_cargo_examples example1 example2` if it's more than "
"one example)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:717
msgid "Cargo examples with flags"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:719
msgid "This script is used for Cargo examples with flags."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:721
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"recipe=\"$(basename \"${COOKBOOK_RECIPE}\")\"\n"
"    for example in example1 example2\n"
"    do\n"
"        \"${COOKBOOK_CARGO}\" build \\\n"
"            --manifest-path \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}/${PACKAGE_PATH}/Cargo."
"toml\" \\\n"
"            --example \"${example}\" \\\n"
"            --release \\\n"
"            --add-your-flag-here\n"
"        mkdir -pv \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}/usr/bin\"\n"
"        cp -v \\\n"
"            \"target/${TARGET}/${build_type}/examples/${example}\" \\\n"
"            \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}/usr/bin/${recipe}_${example}\"\n"
"    done\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:740
msgid ""
"(Replace the `example1` item and others with the example names, if the "
"application has only one example you can remove the `example2` item)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:742
msgid "Rename binaries"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:744
msgid ""
"Some applications or examples use generic names for their executable files "
"which could cause conflicts in the package installation process, to avoid "
"this use the following command after the compilation or installation "
"commands:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:747
msgid ""
"\"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}/usr/bin/binary-name\" \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}/usr/bin/new-"
"binary-name\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:750
msgid "Duplicated names"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:752
msgid ""
"Some recipes for Rust applications can duplicate the application name in the "
"executable (`name_name`), you can also use the command above to fix these "
"cases."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:754
msgid "Change the active source code folder"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:756
msgid ""
"Sometimes a application don't store the source code on the root of the Git "
"repository, but in a subfolder."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:758
msgid ""
"For these cases you need to change the directory of the `${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}` "
"environment variable in the beginning of the `build.script` data type, to do "
"this add the following command on your recipe script:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:761
msgid "\"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}/subfolder-name\""
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:764
msgid "An example for a Rust application:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:766
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"COOKBOOK_SOURCE=\"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}/subfolder-name\"\n"
"cookbook_cargo\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:774
msgid "Configuration Files"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:776
msgid ""
"Some applications require to setup configuration files from the source code "
"or tarball, to setup them use the following script example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:778
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[build]\n"
"template = \"custom\"\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"DYNAMIC_INIT\n"
"cookbook build system function or custom build system commands\n"
"mkdir -pv \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/share # create the /usr/share folder "
"inside the package\n"
"cp -rv \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}\"/configuration-file \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/"
"share # copy the configuration file from the application source code to the "
"package\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:789
msgid "Modify the script above to your needs."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:791
msgid "Script-based applications"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:793
msgid "Read the following scripts to package interpreted applications."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:795
msgid "Adapted scripts"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:797
msgid ""
"This script is for scripts adapted to be packaged, they contain shebangs and "
"renamed the file to remove the script extension."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:799 src/porting-applications.md:831
msgid "(Some applications and libraries need more configuration to work)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:801
msgid "One script"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:803
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"mkdir -pv \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin\n"
"cp \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}\"/script-name \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/script-"
"name\n"
"chmod a+x \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/script-name\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:811
msgid ""
"This script will move the script from the `source` folder to the `stage` "
"folder and mark it as executable to be packaged."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:813
msgid ""
"(Probably you need to mark it as executable, we don't know if all scripts "
"carry executable permission)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:815 src/porting-applications.md:847
msgid "Multiple scripts"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:817
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"mkdir -pv \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin\n"
"cp \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}\"/* \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin\n"
"chmod a+x \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/*\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:825
msgid ""
"This script will move the scripts from the `source` folder to the `stage` "
"folder and mark them as executable to be packaged."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:827
msgid "Non-adapted scripts"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:829
msgid ""
"You need to use the following script examples for scripts not adapted for "
"packaging, you need to add shebangs, rename the file to remove the script "
"extension (`.py`) and mark as executable (`chmod a+x`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:833
msgid "Python script example"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:835
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"mkdir -pv \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin\n"
"cp \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}\"/script-name.py \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/"
"script-name\n"
"chmod a+x \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/script-name\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:843
msgid ""
"(Rename the \"script-name\" parts with your script name and the `.py` "
"extension for your script applicationming language extension if needed)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:845
msgid ""
"This script will rename your script name, make it executable and package."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:849
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"mkdir -pv \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin\n"
"for script in \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}\"/*\n"
"do\n"
"  shortname=`basename \"$script\" \".py\"`\n"
"  cp -v \"$script\" \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/\"$shortname\"\n"
"  chmod a+x \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/\"$shortname\"\n"
"done\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:861
msgid ""
"This script will rename all scripts to remove the `.py` extension, mark all "
"scripts as executable and package."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:863
msgid "Shebang"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:865
msgid ""
"It's the magic behind executable scripts as it make the system interpret the "
"script as an common executable, if your script doesn't have a shebang on the "
"beginning it can't be launched like an conventional compiled application "
"executable."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:867
msgid "To allow this use the following script:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:869
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"mkdir -pv \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin\n"
"cp \"${COOKBOOK_SOURCE}\"/script-name.py \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/"
"script-name\n"
"sed -i '1 i\\#!/usr/bin/env python3' \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/script-"
"name\n"
"chmod a+x \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/script-name\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:878
msgid ""
"The `sed -i '1 i\\#!/usr/bin/env python3' \"${COOKBOOK_STAGE}\"/usr/bin/"
"script-name` command will add the shebang on the beginning of your script."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:880
msgid ""
"The `python3` is the script interpreter in this case, use `bash` or `lua` or "
"whatever interpreter is appropriate for your case."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:882
msgid ""
"There are many combinations for these script examples: you can download "
"scripts without the `[source]` section, make customized installations, etc."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:884
msgid "Dynamically Linked applications"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:886
msgid ""
"The `DYNAMIC_INIT` acts as a marker that indicates the recipe can be "
"dynamically linked, it does the following things:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:889
msgid ""
"Automatically sets `LDFLAGS` and `RUSTFLAGS` based on the preferred linkage"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:890
msgid ""
"Change GNU Autotools defaults to emit `*.so` files and do not create `*.a` "
"files. For executables it setup the appropriate `rpath` link so `*.so` files "
"can be discovered and linked."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:893
msgid ""
"See the environment variables section under configuration settings for more "
"information."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:895
msgid ""
"In most cases if you want to use dynamic linking for a recipe just prepend "
"`DYNAMIC_INIT` in the recipe script. Depending on the recipe, this _should_ "
"suffice. However, sometimes you _may_ need to regenerate the GNU Autotools "
"configuration, which you can do by invoking the "
"`autotools_recursive_regenerate` helper function after `DYNAMIC_INIT` (See "
"the examples below). This is to make sure the build system uses our "
"`libtool` fork. In other cases, more recipe-specific modification may be "
"required."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:903 src/porting-applications.md:935
msgid "Example"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:932
msgid ""
"Dynamically linked applications depend on shared libraries at runtime. To "
"include these libraries, you must add them in the `build.dependencies` data "
"type."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:937
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"# <...snip...>\n"
"\n"
"[build]\n"
"dependencies = [\n"
"    \"libmpc\",\n"
"    \"libgmp\",\n"
"]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:947
msgid "Troubleshooting"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:949
msgid "Why the dynamic linker (`ld.so`) is not finding my library?"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:951
msgid ""
"Set `LD_DEBUG=all` and re-run the application. It will show you where "
"library objects are being found and loaded, as well as the library search "
"paths. You probably forgot to add a library in the `build.dependencies` "
"list. You can also use `patchelf` on your host or on Redox to display all "
"`DT_NEEDED` entries of an object (`patchelf --print-needed <path>`). It is "
"available by default in the `desktop` variant."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:958
msgid "Sources"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:960 src/porting-applications.md:1506
msgid "Tarballs"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:962
msgid ""
"Tarballs are the most easy way to build a C/C++ application or library "
"because the build system is already configured (GNU Autotools is the most "
"used), while being more fast to download and process than big Git "
"repositories if shallow clone is not used (the system don't need to process "
"many Git deltas)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:964 src/porting-applications.md:1008
msgid "Your `recipe.toml` will have the following content:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:966
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[source]\n"
"tar = \"tarball-link\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:971
msgid "Copy the tarball link and paste in the `tarball-link` field."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:973
msgid ""
"**Only use official tarballs**, GitHub auto-generate tarballs for each new "
"release or tag of the application, but they [aren't static](https://github."
"blog/changelog/2023-01-30-git-archive-checksums-may-change/) (break the "
"checksum) and [don't verify the archive integrity](https://github."
"blog/2023-02-21-update-on-the-future-stability-of-source-code-archives-and-"
"hashes/)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:975
msgid ""
"You can find the official tarballs in the release announcement assets with "
"the application name and ending with `tar.gz` or `tar.xz` (their URLs "
"contain \"releases\" instead of \"archive\"), while unstable tarballs can be "
"found on the \"Source code\" buttons (their URLs contain \"archive\")."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:977
msgid ""
"In most cases they are created using the [GNU Tar](https://www.gnu.org/"
"software/tar/) tool."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:978
msgid ""
"Avoid files containing the names \"linux\" and \"x86_64\" on GitHub, they "
"are pre-built binaries for some operating system and CPU architecture, not "
"source code."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:979
msgid ""
"Some applications require Git submodules to work, you can't use tarballs if "
"the official tarball don't bundle the submodules."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:980
msgid ""
"Archives with `tar.xz` and `tar.bz2` are preferred as they tend to have a "
"higher compression level, thus smaller file size."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:982
msgid "Build System"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:984
msgid ""
"In most cases the tarballs use GNU Autotools to build, it's common that the "
"tarball method of compilation is not well documented, causing confusion on "
"new packagers."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:986
msgid "To investigate, you can do the following things:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:988
msgid ""
"Build with the `configure` template and see if it works (sometimes you need "
"to use some flag or customize)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:989
msgid ""
"Search the Git repository of the application or library for `autogen.sh` and "
"`configure.ac` files, it means that support for GNU Autotools is available, "
"when some tarball is created, it comes with a `configure` file inside, this "
"file doesn't exist on the Git repository and you need to create it by "
"running the `autogen.sh` script."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:990
msgid ""
"Sometimes these files are available but GNU Autotools is deprecated (because "
"it's old), we recommend that you use the supported build system (CMake or "
"Meson in most cases)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:992
msgid "Links"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:994
msgid ""
"Sometimes it's hard to find the official tarball of some software, as each "
"project website organization is different."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:996
msgid ""
"To help on this process, the [Arch Linux packages](https://archlinux.org/"
"packages/) and [AUR](https://aur.archlinux.org/) are the most easy "
"repositories to find tarball links in the configuration of packages."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:998
msgid ""
"Arch Linux packages: Search for your application, open the application page, "
"see the \"Package Actions\" category on the top right position and click on "
"the \"Source Files\" button, a GitLab page will open, open the `.SRCINFO` "
"and search for the tarball link on the \"source\" fields of the file."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1000
msgid ""
"See the [nano package](https://gitlab.archlinux.org/archlinux/packaging/"
"packages/nano/-/blob/main/.SRCINFO?ref_type=heads#L12) example."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1002
msgid ""
"AUR: Search for your application, open the application page, go to the "
"\"Sources\" section on the end of the package details."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1004
msgid "Git Repositories"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1006
msgid ""
"Some applications don't offer official tarballs for releases, thus you need "
"to use their Git repository and the branch of the latest stable version (if "
"available) or pin the tag or commit hash of the latest stable version or "
"last working commit."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1010
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[source]\n"
"git = \"repository-link\"\n"
"branch = \"version-branch\"\n"
"rev = \"version-tag\"\n"
"shallow_clone = true\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1018
msgid ""
"Shallow clone is not recommended if you forked the repository and is doing "
"heavy development to port, if you don't want to change the recipe "
"configuration after source fetch run the following command to disable "
"shallow clone temporarily:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1024
msgid "GitHub release"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1026
msgid ""
"Each GitHub release has a tag or commit hash, you will use it to pin the "
"lastest stable version of the application to keep code stability."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1030
msgid ""
"Open the [Rust 1.74 release announcement](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/"
"releases/tag/1.74.0)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1031
msgid ""
"The tag is `1.74.0` and the commit hash is "
"`79e9716c980570bfd1f666e3b16ac583f0168962` and is shortened as `79e9716`"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1033
msgid "GitLab release commit hash"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1035
msgid ""
"Each GitLab release has a tag or commit hash, you will use it to pin the "
"lastest stable version of the application to keep code stability."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1039
msgid ""
"Open the [Redox 0.8.0 release announcement](https://gitlab.redox-os.org/"
"redox-os/redox/-/releases/0.8.0)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1040
msgid ""
"The tag is `0.8.0` and the commit hash is "
"`c8634bd9890afdac4438d1ff99631d600d469264` and is shortened as `c8634bd9`"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1042
msgid "Dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1044
msgid ""
"A application dependency can be a library (a application that offer "
"functions to some application), a runtime (a application that satisfy some "
"application dependency when it's executed) or a build tool (a application to "
"configure/build some application)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1046
msgid ""
"Most C, C++ and Rust applications place build tools/runtime together with "
"development libraries (packages with `-dev` suffix) in their build "
"instructions documentation."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1054
msgid ""
"The `cmake` package is the build system (build tool) while the `libssl-dev` "
"package is the library (OpenSSL) linker objects (`.a` and `.so` files), the "
"Debian package system bundle shared/static objects on their `-dev` packages "
"(other Linux distributions just bundle shared objects)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1056
msgid ""
"You would need to create a recipe of the `libssl-dev` package and add in the "
"`build.dependencies` data type of your `recipe.toml` file, while the `cmake` "
"package would need the `cmake` Cookbook template."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1058
msgid ""
"Dependencies added in the `build.dependencies` data type can be dynamically "
"linked (if the `DYNAMIC_INIT` function is used) or statically linked (if the "
"`DYNAMIC_INIT` function is not used), while dependencies added in the "
"`package.dependencies` data type will be installed by the build system "
"installer or package manager."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1060
msgid ""
"Mixed Rust applications have crates ending with `-sys` to use bundled or "
"system C/C++ libraries."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1062
msgid ""
"If you want an easy way to find dependencies, see the Debian stable "
"[packages list](https://packages.debian.org/stable/allpackages)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1064
msgid ""
"You can search them with Ctrl+F, all package names are clickable and their "
"websites is available on the right-side of the package description/details."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1066
msgid ""
"If you have questions about application dependencies, feel free to ask us on "
"the [Chat](./chat.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1068
msgid "Bundled Libraries"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1070
msgid ""
"Some applications have bundled libraries, using CMake or a Python script, "
"the most common case is using CMake (emulators do this in most cases)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1072
msgid ""
"The reason for this can be control over library versions to avoid "
"compilation/runtime errors or a patched library with optimizations for "
"specific tasks of the application."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1074
msgid ""
"In some cases some bundled library needs a Redox patch, if not it will give "
"a compilation or runtime error."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1076
msgid ""
"Most applications using CMake will try to detect the system libraries on the "
"build environment, if not they will use the bundled libraries."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1078
msgid ""
"The \"system libraries\" on this case is the recipes specified on the `build."
"dependencies = []` section of your `recipe.toml`."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1080
msgid ""
"To determine if you need to use a Redox recipe as dependency check if you "
"find a `.patch` file on the recipe folder or if the `recipe.toml` has a `git "
"=` field pointing to the Redox GitLab, if not you can probably use the "
"bundled libraries without problems."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1082
msgid ""
"Generally applications with CMake use a `-DUSE_SYSTEM` flag to enable the "
"\"system libraries\" behavior."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1086
msgid ""
"Sometimes specify the library recipe on the `dependencies = []` section is "
"not enough, some build systems have environment variables to receive a "
"custom path for external libraries."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1088
msgid ""
"When you add a library on your `recipe.toml` the Cookbook will copy the "
"library source code to the `sysroot` folder at `recipes/your-category/recipe-"
"name/target/$TARGET`, this folder has an environment variable that can be "
"used inside the `script =` field on your `recipe.toml`."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1092
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"export OPENSSL_DIR=\"${COOKBOOK_SYSROOT}\"\n"
"cookbook_cargo\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1099
msgid ""
"The `export` will active the `OPENSSL_DIR` variable on the environment, this "
"variable is implemented by the application build system, it's a way to "
"specify the custom OpenSSL path to the application's build system, as you "
"can see, when the `òpenssl` recipe is added to the `dependencies = []` "
"section its sources go to the `sysroot` folder."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1101
msgid ""
"Now the application build system is satisfied with the OpenSSL sources, the "
"`cookbook_cargo` function calls Cargo to build it."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1103
msgid ""
"applications using CMake don't use environment variables but an option, see "
"this example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1105
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"script = \"\"\"\n"
"COOKBOOK_CMAKE_FLAGS+=(\n"
"    -DOPENSSL_ROOT_DIR=\"${COOKBOOK_SYSROOT}\"\n"
")\n"
"cookbook_cmake\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1114
msgid ""
"On this example the `-DOPENSSL_ROOT_DIR` option will have the custom OpenSSL "
"path."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1116
msgid "Submodules"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1118
msgid ""
"In some applications or libraries you can't use tarballs because they don't "
"carry the necessary Git submodules of the application (most common in GitHub "
"generated tarballs), on these cases you will need to use the Git repository "
"or the commit of the last stable release (Cookbook download the submodules "
"automatically)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1120
msgid ""
"To identify if the application use Git submodules, check if it have external "
"folders to other repository (they appear with a commit hash on the right "
"side) or the existence of a `.gitmodules` file."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1122
msgid ""
"Follow these steps to use the last stable version of the application when "
"Git submodules are necessary:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1124
msgid "Open the application/library Git repository."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1125
msgid ""
"Check the \"Releases\" or \"Tags\" buttons, in most cases the application "
"have a stable release at \"Releases\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1126
msgid ""
"In both pages the commit hash of the stable release will be the first item "
"of the announcement below the version number."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1127
msgid ""
"Copy the repository link/version branch or tag and paste on your `recipe."
"toml`, for example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1129
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"git = \"repository-link\"\n"
"branch = \"version-branch\"\n"
"rev = \"version-tag\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1135
msgid ""
"If the last stable release is too old or lack important fixes due to low "
"maintenance we recommend that you ignore it and use the Git repository to "
"download/build bug fixes sent after this old version, if you are concerned "
"about the application upstream breaking the recipe, you can use the commit "
"of the last successful CI test."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1137
msgid "Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1139
msgid ""
"The determine the application dependencies you can use Arch Linux and Gentoo "
"as reference."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1141
msgid ""
"The build instructions of C/C++ applications tend to mix necessary and "
"optional dependencies together."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1142
msgid ""
"Most Rust applications have build instructions focused on Linux and force "
"some dependencies, some crates could not need them to work, investigate "
"which crates the application is using."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1143
msgid ""
"Some applications and libraries have bad documentation, lack build "
"instructions or explain the dependencies, for these cases you will need to "
"read third-party sources or examine the build system."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1145
msgid ""
"Arch Linux and AUR are the most simple references because they separate the "
"build tools from runtimes and build dependencies, thus you make less "
"mistakes."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1147
msgid ""
"They also have less expanded packages, while on Debian is common to have "
"highly expanded applications and libraries, sometimes causing confusion."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1149
msgid ""
"(An expanded package is when most or all optional dependencies are enabled)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1151
msgid ""
"But Arch Linux is not clear about the optional feature flags and minimum "
"dependencies to build and execute a application."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1153
msgid ""
"Using Gentoo as reference you can learn how to make the most minimum Redox "
"port and increase your chances to make it work on Redox."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1155
msgid ""
"But Gentoo modify the feature flags of their packages to be used by their "
"package system, thus you should use the FreeBSD Ports."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1157
msgid "Arch Linux and AUR"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1159
msgid ""
"Each package page of some application has a \"Dependencies\" section on the "
"package details, see the items below:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1161
msgid ""
"`dependency-name` - Build or runtime dependencies, they lack the `()` symbol "
"(required to make the application build and execute)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1162
msgid ""
"`dependency-name (make)` - Build tools (required to build the application)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1163
msgid ""
"`dependency-name (optional)` - applications or libraries to expand the "
"application functionality"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1165
msgid ""
"See the [firefox package](https://archlinux.org/packages/extra/x86_64/"
"firefox/), for example."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1167
msgid "[Arch Linux Packages](https://archlinux.org/packages/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1168
msgid "[AUR](https://aur.archlinux.org/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1170
msgid "Gentoo"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1172
msgid ""
"The [Gentoo](https://gentoo.org) distribution does a wonderful job to "
"document many applications and libraries, like source code location, "
"dependencies, feature flags, cross-compilation and context."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1174
msgid ""
"It's the most complete reference for advanced packaging of applications, you "
"can search the Gentoo packages on the [Gentoo Packages](https://packages."
"gentoo.org/) website."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1176
msgid ""
"To start you need to read the [Gentoo documentation](https://devmanual."
"gentoo.org/general-concepts/dependencies/) page to learn advanced packaging "
"and some problems."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1178
msgid ""
"The \"Dependencies\" section of a Gentoo package will show a table with the "
"following categories:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1180
msgid ""
"`BDEPEND` - Host build tools (don't add them on the `dependencies = []` "
"section of your `recipe.toml`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1181
msgid "`DEPEND` - These dependencies are necessary to build the application"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1182
msgid ""
"`RDEPEND` - These dependencies are necessary to execute the application, can "
"be mandatory or optional"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1183
msgid "`PDEPEND` - Optional dependencies (customization)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1185
msgid ""
"The complex classification of Gentoo allow the packager to easily make a "
"minimum build of a application on Redox, it's important because some "
"optional dependencies can use APIs from the Linux kernel not present on "
"Redox."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1187
msgid ""
"Thus the best approach is to know the minimum necessary to make the "
"application work on Redox and expand from that."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1189
msgid "Build Tools"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1191
msgid ""
"Add missing recipe build tools in the [podman/redox-base-containerfile]"
"(https://gitlab.redox-os.org/redox-os/redox/-/blob/master/podman/redox-base-"
"containerfile) file (for Podman builds) or install them on your system (for "
"Native builds)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1193
msgid ""
"The `podman/redox-base-containerfile` file and `native_bootstrap.sh` script "
"covers the build tools required by recipes on the [demo.toml](https://gitlab."
"redox-os.org/redox-os/redox/-/blob/master/config/x86_64/demo.toml) "
"filesystem configuration."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1195
msgid "Feature Flags"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1197
msgid ""
"The application/library build systems offer flags to enable/disable "
"features, it will increase the chance to make them work on Redox by "
"disabling Linux-specific or unsupported features/libraries."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1199
msgid ""
"Sometimes you need to read the build system configuration to find important "
"or all flags that weren't documented by the application."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1201
msgid "Cargo"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1203
msgid ""
"You can find the feature flags below the `[features]` section in the `Cargo."
"toml` file."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1205
msgid "GNU Autotools"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1207
msgid ""
"You can find the feature flags in the `INSTALL`, `README` or `configure` "
"files."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1209
msgid "CMake"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1211
msgid "You can find the feature flags in the `CMakeLists.txt` file."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1213
msgid "Meson"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1215
msgid "You can find the feature flags in the `meson_options` file."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1217
msgid "FreeBSD Reference"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1219
msgid ""
"If you can't find the application build system flags the FreeBSD port "
"Makefiles are the best reference for feature flags to Redox as they tend to "
"disable Linux-specific features and are adapted to cross-compilation, "
"increasing the application/library compatiblity with non-Linux systems."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1221
msgid ""
"(You need to disable the application/library's build system tests to make "
"cross-compilation work)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1223
msgid "[FreeBSD Ports GitHub Mirror](https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd-ports)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1225
msgid "(Use the \"Go to file\" button to search for the software name)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1227
msgid "Building/Testing The application"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1229
msgid ""
"Tip: If you want to avoid problems not related to Redox install the "
"application dependencies and build to your system first (if packages for "
"your Unix-like distribution aren't available search for Debian/Ubuntu "
"equivalents)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1231
msgid "To build your recipe, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1237
msgid ""
"If you get an error read the log and determine if it is one of the following "
"problems:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1239
msgid "Missing build tools"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1240
msgid "Cross-compilation configuration problem"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1241
msgid "Lack of Redox patches"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1242
msgid "Missing C, POSIX or Linux library functions in relibc"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1244
msgid "Use this command to log any possible errors on your terminal output:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1250
msgid ""
"If the compilation was successful the recipe can be installed in the QEMU "
"image and tested inside of Redox to find possible runtime errors or crashes."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1252
msgid ""
"To temporarily install the recipe to your QEMU image run `make p.recipe-name`"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1253
msgid ""
"To permanently install the recipe to your QEMU image add your recipe name "
"(`recipe-name = {}`) below the last item in the `[packages]` section of your "
"TOML config at `config/$ARCH/your-config.toml` and run `make image`"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1255
msgid "To test your recipe inside of Redox with Orbital, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1261
msgid "If you only want to test in the Redox terminal interface, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1267
msgid "Update crates"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1269
msgid ""
"Sometimes the `Cargo.toml` and `Cargo.lock` of some Rust applications can "
"hold a crate versions lacking Redox support or a broken Redox code path "
"(changes on code that make the target OS fail), this will give you an error "
"during the recipe compilation."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1271
msgid ""
"The reason of fixed crate versions is explained on the [Cargo FAQ](https://"
"doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/faq.html#why-do-binaries-have-cargolock-in-version-"
"control-but-not-libraries)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1273
msgid ""
"To fix this you will need to update the crates of your recipe after the "
"first compilation and build it again, see the ways to do it below."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1275
msgid ""
"(Bump a crate version on `Cargo.toml` can break some part of the source "
"code, on this case the application needs a source code patch to use the "
"updated API of the crate)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1277
msgid "One or more crates"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1279
msgid ""
"In maintained Rust applications you just need to update some crates to have "
"Redox support (because they frequently update the crate versions), this will "
"avoid random breaks on the dependency chain of the application (due to ABI "
"changes) thus you can update one or more crates to reduce the chance of "
"breaks."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1281
msgid ""
"We recommend that you do this based on the errors you get during the "
"compilation, this method is recommended for maintained applications."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1283 src/porting-applications.md:1321
msgid ""
"Expose the Redox build system environment variables to the current shell, go "
"to the `source` folder of your recipe and update the crates, example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1305 src/porting-applications.md:1343
#: src/porting-applications.md:1402
msgid "If you still get the error, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1311
msgid "All crates"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1313
msgid ""
"Most unmaintained Rust applications carry very old crate versions with "
"lacking/broken Redox support, this method will update all crates of the "
"dependency chain to the latest possible version based on the `Cargo.toml` "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1315
msgid ""
"Be aware that some crates break the API stability frequently and make the "
"applications stop to work, that's why you must try the \"One crate\" method "
"first."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1317
msgid ""
"This method can fix locked crate versions on the dependency tree, if these "
"locked crate versions don't change you need to bump the version of the "
"crates locking the crate version, you will edit them in the `Cargo.toml` and "
"run `cargo update` again (API breaks are expected)."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1319
msgid "(Also good to test the latest improvements of the libraries)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1349
msgid "Verify the dependency tree"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1351
msgid ""
"If you use the above methods but the application is still using old crate "
"versions, see this section:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1353
msgid ""
"[Verify the dependency tree](./troubleshooting.md#verify-the-dependency-tree)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1355
msgid "Patch crates"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1357
msgid "Redox forks"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1359
msgid ""
"It's possible that some not ported crate have a Redox fork with patches, you "
"can search the crate name on the [Redox GitLab](https://gitlab.redox-os."
"org/), generally the Redox patches stay in the `redox` branch or `redox-"
"version` branch that follow the crate version."
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1361
msgid ""
"To use this Redox fork on your Rust application, add this text on the end of "
"the `Cargo.toml` in the application source code:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1363
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[patch.crates-io]\n"
"crate-name = { git = \"repository-link\", branch = \"redox\" }\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1368
msgid ""
"It will make Cargo replace the patched crate in the entire dependency chain, "
"after that, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1374
msgid "Or (if the above doesn't work)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1408
msgid "Local patches"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1410
msgid ""
"If you want to patch some crate offline with your patches, add this text on "
"the `Cargo.toml` of the application:"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1412
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[patch.crates-io]\n"
"crate-name = { path = \"patched-crate-folder\" }\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1417
msgid ""
"It will make Cargo replace the crate based on this folder in the application "
"source code - `recipes/your-category/your-recipe/source/patched-crate-"
"folder` (you don't need to manually create this folder if you `git clone` "
"the crate source code on the application source directory)"
msgstr ""

#: src/porting-applications.md:1419
msgid ""
"Inside this folder you will apply the patches on the crate source and "
"rebuild the recipe."
msgstr ""

